    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-02-09T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-02-09T05:00:00-05:00" n="35"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d35">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72114/3285</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Switzerland</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_WHR1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wilson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berne</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-02-09T11:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 9, 1918, 11 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received February 11, 5.20 a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2607. Department’s 1307, January 8.<note n="1" xml:id="d35fn1">See footnote 1,
                            <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_18">p. 18</ref>.</note>
                    Swiss Government replies will gladly undertake free transmission for present of
                    letters, money orders, and packages under 5 kilograms directed to American
                    prisoners of war and interned civilians in Germany, Austria-Hungary, Bulgaria
                    and Turkey although United States not a signatory of Rome postal
                        convention.<note n="2" xml:id="d35fn2">Reference is apparently made to the
                        Universal Postal Convention signed at Rome May 26, 1906; but the United
                        States <hi rend="italic">was</hi> a signatory of this convention (35 Stat.
                        1639).</note> Should number of packages increase greatly, postage of 25
                    centimes per parcel may be asked as already required from France, Great Britain,
                    Italy, Germany and Austria-Hungary.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_WHR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
